\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 20. E. spinalba} Vill., {\i Prosp. Pl. Dauph.} 26 (1779). Perennial; stems 20-35 cm, very stout. Basal leaves coriaceous; lamina 5-8 × 5-10 cm, suborbicular, cordate at base, palmatifid or palmatisect with (3-)4-5 irregularly pinnatifid segments with large, spinescent teeth throughout; petiole about twice as long as lamina, unwinged. Inflorescence usually bluish, with up to 10 pedunculate, ovoid-cylindrical capitula 4-6 × 2-3 cm. Bracts 6-9 cm, 15-30, linear-lanceolate, often 3-fid, with numerous spinescent teeth, pungent; bracteoles mostly 3-cuspidate. Sepals c. 3·5 mm, linear-lanceolate, aristate. Fruit densely scaly. {\i Dry, stony places on mountains. • S.W. Alps.} Ga It.
\par

